@node Text Transformation Tables (TTT), Message Priority Model, User Authentication, Features
@subsection Text Transformation Tables
@cindex TTT

The mechanism that Speech Dispatcher provides for processing
punctuation, capital letters, spelling or keys and characters,
is based on text tables mapping the required characters to some
text or a sound.

When Speech Dispatcher receives a command like @code{CHAR "a"},
it finds which table to use and according to it's content
produces either a some sound (.wav or .ogg) or some text
("ai", "alice", "acko", ...). All of this can be configured
through tables.

These tables, unless specified otherwise, are language-specific,
so that a user can specify different spelling rules for English
than for Czech or Italian.

@menu
* TTT Types::                   List of supported Text Transformation Tables.
@end menu

@node TTT Types,  , Text Transformation Tables (TTT), Text Transformation Tables (TTT)
@subsubsection TTT Types

There are currently 6 types of tables in Speech Dispatcher:

@itemize
@item Spelling (group @code{spelling})
This is used in spelling modes.

@item Punctuation (group @code{punctuation})
This is used in punctuation modes.

@item Capital Letter Recognition (group @code{cap_let_recogn})
This is used when capital letters recognition is set to spell the capital
letters.

@item Character (group @code{characters})
This is used when the client application wants to read a single
character, eg. when the user moves with cursor over text.

@item Key (group @code{keys})
This one is used when the user presses in keys, eg. when typing in some
text.

@item Sound icons (group @code{sound_icons})
These sound icons used to signal some events, e.g. end-of-line
or new-mail.
@end itemize

The user can set different tables for all of these situations, although
there is no need to and two or three tables for each language is enough.
For example the events Spelling, Punctuation and Character can be mapped
to the same table.

See @ref{Tables Configuration} to find out how to configure text
transformation tables.


