@subsubsection Adding and Choosing Tables

Each table has a specific file and each of these files you want to use must
be loaded into Speech Dispatcher before it's possible to use it. It can be
done using this option in @file{speechd.conf}

@code{AddTable "@var{table_filename}"}

@var{table_filename} is the path to the desired table. It can be
either absolute or relative (to your @file{etc/speechd/} directory).

For example, the default English tables are loaded like this:

@example
AddTable        "en/spelling_short.conf"
AddTable        "en/spelling_long.conf"
AddTable        "en/sound_icons.conf"
AddTable        "en/keys.conf"
@end example

If you use tables for more languages, you must load them also, to be
able to use them.

Once the tables are loaded, you can specify which table should be
used in which mode by default. (They can be then changed by clients
at run-time). There are six configuration options
to do this.

@itemize
@item DefaultSpellingTable "@var{table}"
@item DefaultPunctuationTable "@var{table}"
@item DefaultCharacterTable "@var{table}"
@item DefaultCapLetRecognTable "@var{table}"
@item DefaultKeyTable "@var{table}"
@item DefaultSoundTable "@var{table}"
@end itemize

@var{table} is the name of the table specified in the file. Note that
this doesn't have to coincide with it's filename and also
it is language independent (the right table according to the
selected language will be chosen from available tables with
this name).

This is a valid definition of default tables:

@example
DefaultSpellingTable      "spelling_short"
DefaultPunctuationTable   "spelling_short"
DefaultCharacterTable     "spelling_short"
DefaultCapLetRecognTable  "spelling_short"
DefaultKeyTable           "keys"
DefaultSoundTable         "sound_icons"
@end example

Note that it's possible to use the same table for various modes.

@node Writing tables and modifying,  , Adding and choosing tables, Tables Configuration
@subsubsection Writing and Modifying Tables

In the header of each table, three things must be specified:

@table @code
@item language:@var{language_code}
@var{language_code} is the ISO code of the language this table is written for.

@item table:@var{table_name}
@var{table_name} is the name of the table. This allows you to have one
table split into more files or redefine some entries in an existing
table. If you are going to create a new table, chose some unique
name. If the table is specific for some application, prefix it's name
with the name of the application and an underscore
(eg. @code{emacs_sound_icons}).

@item group:@var{group_name}
Some tables, such as the spelling tables, are often also useful for other
things like punctuation or characters reading, however there is no use
for it in sound icons or keys reading, because the entries here have
different names and mean different things. You should specify here
in which groups this table can be used (if your table is specificly
designed for one thing, keep the group: list minimal). There
should be at least one entry.

@var{group_name} is the name of the group this table can be used
in.  See @ref{TTT Types}, for possible arguments.
@end table

Each header must be terminated with the string @code{definition:} on 
a separate line.

In @file{en/spelling_short.conf} we use this header

@example
language:en

table:spelling_short

group:spelling
group:characters
group:punctuation
group:cap_let_recogn

definition:
@end example

The definition of all the entries follow, each on one line, in this form:

@code{"name" = "@var{text}"}
or
@code{"name" = @var{path_to_sound_file}}

You can specify the @code{text} that should be synthesized for this
entry (in double quotes) or a @var{path_to_sound_file} that should
be played (without double quotes). This path can be either relative
(to the directory specified by the SoundDataDir option in configuration
or to your @file{usr/share/sounds/speechd} if SoundDataDir is not set)
or absolute. Currently supported sound files include .wav and
.ogg.

Examples are:

@example
"A"="capital ai"
"B"="capital b"

"warning" = "warning!"
"error" = error.ogg
"new-mail" = /usr/local/share/sounds/sound-library/notify-new-mail.wav
@end example

@node Log Levels,  , Tables Configuration, Configuration
@subsection Log Levels

There are 6 different verbosity levels of Speech Dispatcher logging.
0 means no logging, while 5 means that nearly all the information
about Speech Dispatcher's operation is logged.

@itemize @bullet

@item Level 0
@itemize @bullet
@item No information.
@end itemize

@item Level 1
@itemize @bullet
@item Information about loading and exiting.
@end itemize

@item Level 2
@itemize @bullet
@item Information about errors that occurred.
@item Allocating and freeing resources on start and exit.
@end itemize

@item Level 3
@itemize @bullet
@item Information about accepting/rejecting/closing clients' connections.
@item Information about invalid client commands.
@end itemize

@item Level 4
@itemize @bullet
@item Every received command is output.
@item Information about proceeding the command output
@item Information about queueing/allocating messages.
@item Information about the function of history, sound icons and other
facilities.
@item Information about the work of the speak() thread.
@end itemize

@item Level 5
(This is only for debugging purposes and can output really *much*
data. Use with caution.)
@itemize @bullet
@item Also received data (messages etc.) is output.
@end itemize
@end itemize


